'''Hakan Çalhanoğlu'''<ref name="FIFA U-20 2013">{{cite web |url=http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWYC/2013/pdf/FWYC_2013_SquadLists.pdf |title=FIFA U-20 World Cup Turkey 2013 List of Players: Turkey |work=FIFA.com |page=21 |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Associationplayed for inter Milan 2020 |date=23 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627043508/http://www.fifadata.com/document/FWYC/2013/pdf/FWYC_2013_SquadLists.pdf |archive-date=27 June 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> ({{IPA|tr|ˈhaːkan ˈtʃaɫhanoːɫu}}, born 8 February 1994) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder|defensive midfielder]] for {{Italian football updater|Internazionale}} club [[Inter Milan]]. Born in Germany, he plays for and [[Captain (association football)|captains]] the [[Turkey national football team|Turkey national team]]. He is regarded as amongst the best midfielders in the world.<ref name=cal>{{cite web|url=https://football-italia.net/how-calhanoglu-has-become-one-of-the-best-midfielders-in-the-world-at-inter-under-inzaghi/|title=How Calhanoglu has become one of the best midfielders in the world at Inter under Inzaghi|publisher=Football Italia|date=6 February 2024}}</ref>

Çalhanoğlu began his career at [[2. Bundesliga|German second division]] club [[Karlsruher SC]] in 2010 and moved to [[Bundesliga|top-flight]] side [[Hamburger SV]] two years later, spending another season back at his first club on loan. His performance in his first Bundesliga season earned him a €14.5 million transfer to [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] in 2014. He played for three seasons there, totalling 28 goals in 115 official appearances. In 2017, Çalhanoğlu signed for [[AC Milan]] for an initial €20 million fee, before joining [[Derby della Madonnina|city rivals]] Inter on a free transfer in the summer of 2021.

Born in [[Germany]], Çalhanoğlu represents Turkey at international level, from [[Turkey national youth football team|under-16 level]] onwards. He made his senior debut in 2013, and was part of their squad at the [[UEFA European Championship]] in [[UEFA Euro 2016|2016]], [[UEFA Euro 2020|2020]] and [[UEFA Euro 2024|2024]].

==Club career==

===Karlsruher SC===
Born in [[Mannheim]], [[Baden-Württemberg]], Germany, Çalhanoğlu began his career with [[Karlsruher SC]] in the [[2. Bundesliga]] in February 2012 after he was promoted from the under-19 team, although they were relegated to the [[3. Liga]] at the end of his first season. He signed a four-year deal to join [[Hamburger SV]] in the 2012 summer transfer window, being loaned back to Karlsruhe for another season.<ref name=fifa>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/news/calhanoglu-great-opportunity-2019132|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624202034/https://www.fifa.com/news/calhanoglu-great-opportunity-2019132|url-status=dead|archive-date=24 June 2021|title=Calhanoglu: A great opportunity|publisher=FIFA|date=27 February 2013|access-date=30 June 2013}}</ref> In that season on loan, he helped the team win the third division and return to the second tier.

===Hamburger SV===
Çalhanoğlu made his Hamburg and [[Bundesliga]] debut on 11 August 2013, as the team opened the season with a 3–3 away draw at [[FC Schalke 04|Schalke 04]]. He started the match, and was replaced by [[Dennis Aogo]] after 74 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Schalke make point|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/294912/report|access-date=16 April 2015|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=11 August 2013}}</ref> He scored his first goals for the club on 31 August, in a 4–0 home win over [[Eintracht Braunschweig]]; after replacing goalscorer [[Rafael van der Vaart]] in the 79th minute, he scored a minute later and then netted again with a free kick.<ref>{{cite web|title=No problems for Hamburg|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/290930/report|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=Sky Sports|date=31 August 2013}}</ref>

On 5 February 2014, Çalhanoğlu signed a two-year extension to his Hamburg contract, to keep him at the club until 2018.<ref>{{cite web |date=5 February 2014 |title=Calhanoglu pens new Hamburg contract |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/calhanoglu-pens-new-hamburg-contract |access-date=6 March 2015 |website=[[FourFourTwo]]}}</ref> On 20 February, he scored a 41-yard free kick, against [[Borussia Dortmund]] in a 3–0 win, which ended Hamburg's bad run. As he saw no defensive wall or teammates to pass, he struck a shot that swerved viciously to find the back of the net. A delighted Çalhanoğlu said afterwards: 'I hit the free-kick the same way I do in training all the time. I'm delighted that I pulled it off!'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/sports/calhanoglu-s-40-metre-shot-tops-stunning-bundesliga-goals-idUSDEEA1M02J/ |title=Calhanoglu's 40-metre shot tops stunning Bundesliga goals |publisher=Reuters |date=23 February 2014 }}</ref> He was sent off for the first time in his career on 22 March, for his second booking in the 53rd minute of a 1–0 defeat away to [[VfB Stuttgart]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Take it to the Maxim|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/live/match/291261/report|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=Sky Sports|date=22 March 2014}}</ref>

In [[2013–14 Bundesliga|his only full season at Hamburg]], the team finished in 16th, and won a play-off against [[SpVgg Greuther Fürth|Greuther Fürth]] on away goals to maintain their honour as the only team to feature in every season of the top flight.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Raish|first1=Dave|title=Hamburg secure Bundesliga survival over Greuther Fürth in relegation play-off|url=http://www.dw.de/hamburg-secure-bundesliga-survival-over-greuther-f%C3%BCrth-in-relegation-playoff/a-17644357|access-date=6 March 2015|work=[[Deutsche Welle]]|date=18 May 2014}}</ref>

===Bayer Leverkusen===
[[File:Hakan Calhanoglu 2014.jpg|thumb|left|175px|Çalhanoğlu warming up with Leverkusen before a friendly in July 2014]]
Hamburg were initially unwilling to sell Çalhanoğlu to other German teams, but their purchase of [[Pierre-Michel Lasogga]] from [[Hertha BSC|Hertha Berlin]] made such an exception no longer financially viable.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Uersfeld|first1=Stephen|title=Hakan Calhanoglu in Leverkusen move|url=https://www.espnfc.com/story/1931864/hamburg-midfielder-hakan-calhanoglu-joins-leverkusen|access-date=29 August 2015|publisher=[[ESPN FC]]|date=4 July 2014}}</ref> On 4 July 2014, he left Hamburg for league rivals [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]], signing a five-year contract<ref>{{cite web |date=4 July 2014 |title=Leverkusen complete Calhanoglu deal |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/leverkusen-complete-calhanoglu-deal |access-date=6 March 2015 |website=[[FourFourTwo]]}}</ref> for a transfer fee of €14.5 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Advantage Leverkusen as classy Calhanoglu cements status as rising star|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/7221/nissan/2015/02/26/9291532/advantage-leverkusen-as-classy-calhanoglu-cements-status-as|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=Goal.com|date=26 February 2015}}</ref> His actions leading up to the transfer caused some controversy, including taking [[sick leave]] from Hamburg; he justified the leave by saying that he was stressed by aggression from fans, including vandalism of his car. He also criticised Hamburg's director [[Oliver Kreuzer]], accusing him of betrayal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Calhanoglu: "Kreuzer ist mir in den Rücken gefallen"|trans-title=Çalhanoğlu: "Kreuzer stabbed me in the back"|url=https://www.t-online.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga/id_71451008/hakan-calhanoglu-auto-wurde-kaputtgeschlagen-.html|access-date=29 August 2015|publisher=T-Online|date=19 October 2014|language=de}}</ref> The move was later criticised by [[Son Heung-min]], as a response to Çalhanoğlu calling his former Leverkusen teammate's transfer to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] "badly advised".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Uersfeld|first1=Stephan|title=Son Heung-Min badly advised over Tottenham move – Hakan Calhanoglu|url=https://www.espnfc.com/story/2583784/son-heung-min-ill-advised-over-spurs-move-hakan-calhanoglu|access-date=29 August 2015|publisher=ESPN FC|date=27 August 2015}}</ref>

He made his debut for the club on 19 June, starting in a 3–2 away win at [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] in the first leg of a [[UEFA Champions League]] qualification play-off.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leverkusen edge København in first-leg thriller|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/025a-0ea794031f6e-808fb2b953d2-1000--leverkusen-edge-kobenhavn-in-first-leg-thriller/|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=UEFA|date=19 August 2014}}</ref> Four days later, he played his first league game for his new club, a 2–0 win away to [[Borussia Dortmund]] on the opening day of [[2014–15 Bundesliga|the new season]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Borussia Dortmund 0–2 Bayer Leverkusen: BVB rocked by record-breaker Bellarabi|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/borussia-dortmund-vs-bayer-leverkusen/1713097/report?ICID=MP_MS_5|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=Goal.com|date=23 August 2014}}</ref> On 27 August he scored his first Leverkusen goal, netting his team's second in a 4–0 win in the second leg of their European play-off.<ref>{{cite web|title=Leverkusen coast through at FCK's expense|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0253-0d041cef3704-60a9ae044daa-1000--leverkusen-coast-through-at-fck-s-expense/|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=UEFA|date=27 August 2014}}</ref> He scored his first league goal for the club on 12 September, Leverkusen's second in a 3–3 home draw against [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]]. It was the first game in any competition that season which they did not win.<ref>{{cite news |date=12 September 2014 |title=Bayer Leverkusen rue missed chances as Werder Bremen snatch late point |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/sep/12/bayer-leverkusen-werder-bremen |access-date=6 March 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Çalhanoğlu was nominated for the 2014 [[Golden Boy (award)|Golden Boy Award]] in October.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Richards|first1=Alex|title=England pair Raheem Sterling and Calum Chambers join Adnan Januzaj in Golden Boy award nominations|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/england-pair-raheem-sterling-calum-4523237|access-date=28 October 2014|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=28 October 2014}}</ref>

[[File:Hakan-Calhanoglu-2015-08.jpg|thumb|upright|175px|Çalhanoğlu with Leverkusen in 2015]]
On 25 February 2015, he scored the only goal as Leverkusen defeated [[Atlético Madrid]] in the last 16 first leg in the Champions League.<ref>{{cite news |last=Raynor |first=Dominic |date=25 February 2015 |title=Bayer Leverkusen 1–0 Atletico Madrid |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31608958 |access-date=26 February 2015 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref> However, three weeks later in the second leg, he took their first attempt in a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] and had it saved by [[Jan Oblak]], as Atlético went on to win.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Jonathan|title=Atlético Madrid 1–0 Bayer 04 Leverkusen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31911679|access-date=18 March 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 March 2015}}</ref> On 2 May, Çalhanoğlu opened a 2–0 home win over newly crowned league champions [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], with a free kick.<ref>{{cite news |date=2 May 2015 |title=Bayer Leverkusen 2–0 Bayern Munich |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32553139 |access-date=3 May 2015 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref>

He opened his second season at the club by scoring a penalty on 8 August in a 3–0 win at fourth-tier [[Sportfreunde Lotte]] in the first round of the [[DFB-Pokal]].<ref>{{cite web |date=8 August 2015 |title=DFB-Pokal: Wolfsburg win, Hoffenheim fall |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/37428111/wolfsburg-leverkusen-schalke-all-win-dfb-pokal-openers |access-date=8 August 2015 |website=ESPN}}</ref> Two weeks later, with a free kick, he scored the only goal of a league win at [[Hannover 96]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Freistoß-König Calhanoglu lsst Leverkusen jubeln!|trans-title=Free-kick king Çalhanoğlu lets Leverkusen cheer!|url=http://www.bild.de/bundesliga/1-liga/saison-2015-2016/spielbericht-hannover-96-gegen-bayer-04-leverkusen-am-2-Spieltag-41724490.bild.html|access-date=24 October 2015|work=[[Bild]]|date=22 October 2015|language=de|archive-date=11 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711010302/http://www.bild.de/bundesliga/1-liga/saison-2015-2016/spielbericht-hannover-96-gegen-bayer-04-leverkusen-am-2-Spieltag-41724490.bild.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 26 August, he opened a 3–0 win over [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] as Bayer came back from a first-leg deficit to qualify for the [[2015–16 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]] of the Champions League.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |date=27 August 2015 |title=Champions League roundup: Bayer Leverkusen ease past Lazio |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/aug/27/champions-league-riundup-bayer-leverkusen |access-date=27 August 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In their first game of the group stage, Çalhanoğlu scored twice — including a penalty earned by a handball of his free kick — in a 4–1 home rout of [[FC BATE Borisov|BATE Borisov]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bayer Leverkusen 4–1 BATE Borisov: Big win for Bundesliga side|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11891/9993739/bayer-leverkusen-4-1-bate-borisov-big-win-for-bundesliga-side|access-date=24 October 2015|publisher=Sky Sports|date=16 September 2015}}</ref>

He opened his [[2016–17 Bayer 04 Leverkusen season|2016–17]] goalscoring account on 14 September in the 2–2 home draw against [[PFC CSKA Moscow|CSKA Moscow]] in a Champions League group stage game — the 50th goal in his senior club career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espnfc.us/report?gameId=466245|title=Dzagoev fires CSKA Moscow rally in draw with Bayer Leverkusen|publisher=ESPN FC|date=14 September 2016|access-date=23 September 2016}}</ref>

On 2 February 2017, Çalhanoğlu received a four-month ban from [[FIFA]] for a breach of contract relating to his time at Karlsruher SC. He received €100,000 from Turkish club [[Trabzonspor]] in 2011 after agreeing to sign with the club but later extended his contract with Karlsruhe. Trabzonspor had initially sought repayment of the €100,000 paid as well compensation of €1 million but FIFA ruled that €100,000 and a four-month ban would suffice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/bayer-leverkusen/story/3052373/bayer-leverkusen-midfielder-hakan-calhanoglu-to-serve-four-month-ban-from-fifa|title=Bayer Leverkusen midfielder Hakan Calhanoglu to serve four-month ban from FIFA|website=ESPN|date=2 February 2017|access-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>

===AC Milan===
On 3 July 2017, Çalhanoğlu signed a four-year contract with [[Serie A]] club [[AC Milan]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.acmilan.com/en/news/official-statement/2017-07-03/official-calhanoglu-is-now-red-and-black|title=Official: Calhanoglu is now red and black|date=3 July 2017|access-date=3 July 2017|publisher=A.C. Milan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=3 July 2017 |title=Milan sign Calhanoglu from Leverkusen |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/story/_/id/37525781/ac-milan-sign-hakan-calhanoglu-bayer-leverkusen |access-date=18 April 2025 |website=ESPN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=3 July 2017 |title=OFFICIAL: AC Milan sign Çalhanoğlu on a four-year deal |url=https://sempremilan.com/official-ac-milan-sign-calhanoglu-four-year-deal |access-date=18 April 2025 |website=SempreMilan}}</ref> The fee was reported as an initial €20 million, rising to €24 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=AC Milan sign Hakan Calhanoglu from Bayer Leverkusen|url=https://www.espnfc.com/story/3152144/ac-milan-sign-hakan-calhanoglu-from-bayer-leverkusen|access-date=7 September 2017|publisher=ESPN|date=3 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Hakan Calhanoglu Completes AC Milan Move |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/serie-a/articles/hakan-calhanoglu-completes-ac-milan-move-2 |access-date=18 April 2025 |website=beIN SPORTS |language=en-us}}</ref> He was assigned the club's prestigious [[Squad number (association football)|number 10 jersey]], previously owned by the likes of [[Gianni Rivera]], [[Ruud Gullit]], [[Dejan Savićević]], [[Zvonimir Boban]], [[Rui Costa]], [[Clarence Seedorf]] and [[Keisuke Honda]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Joshi|first1=Vishal|title=Milan Issue Latest Recruits Shirt Numbers as Calhanoglu, Bonucci, Silva & Rodrigues Learn Their Fate|url=http://www.90min.com/posts/5388464-milan-issue-latest-recruits-shirt-numbers-as-calhanoglu-bonucci-silva-rodrigues-learn-their-fate|access-date=7 September 2017|publisher=90 Min|date=12 August 2017|archive-date=8 June 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608061744/https://www.90min.com/posts/5388464-milan-issue-latest-recruits-shirt-numbers-as-calhanoglu-bonucci-silva-rodrigues-learn-their-fate|url-status=dead}}</ref>

He made his ''Rossoneri'' competitive debut a month later in the second leg of the Europa League third qualifying round, replacing [[Suso (footballer)|Suso]] for the final 25 minutes of a 2–0 win (3–0 aggregate) over [[CS Universitatea Craiova|Universitatea Craiova]] at the [[San Siro]].<ref>{{cite news|title=AC Milan 2 CSU Craiova 0 (3–0 agg): Cutrone's first goal seals Europa League progress|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/ac-milan-2-csu-craiova-0-3-0-agg-cutrones-first-goal-seals-europa-league-progress|access-date=7 September 2017|work=FourFourTwo|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Milan in a 5–1 away win against [[FK Austria Wien|Austria Wien]] in the group stage on 14 September, also providing two assists.<ref>{{cite news|title=Austria Vienna 1–5 AC Milan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41227391|access-date=10 October 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=14 September 2017}}</ref> Domestically, Çalhanoğlu made his league debut on 20 August, playing the full 90 minutes of a 3–0 win at [[F.C. Crotone|Crotone]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Patrick Cutrone catches the eye as AC Milan start with convincing win at Crotone|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report?gameId=491677|access-date=10 October 2017|agency=PA Sport|publisher=ESPN FC|date=21 August 2017}}</ref> He was sent off in a 2–0 home loss to [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] on 1 October, earning a second yellow card for a foul on [[Radja Nainggolan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=AC Milan 0 Roma 2: Dzeko, Florenzi pounce to leave Montella in trouble|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/ac-milan-0-roma-2-dzeko-florenzi-pounce-leave-montella-trouble#r3z-addoor|access-date=10 October 2017|work=FourFourTwo|date=1 October 2017}}</ref> Çalhanoğlu scored his first league goal on 25 October in a 4–1 win at [[A.C. ChievoVerona|Chievo]], becoming the first Turk to net in Serie A since [[Emre Belözoğlu]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suso stars in Milan win over Chievo to ease pressure in Montella|url=http://www.beinsports.com/us/serie-a/video/suso-stars-in-milan-win-over-chievo-to-ease-p/690219|access-date=25 October 2017|publisher=beIN Sports|date=25 October 2017}}</ref>

===Inter Milan===
[[File:Edison Ndreca Inter (cropped Hakan Çalhanoğlu).jpg|thumb|left|175px|Çalhanoğlu with Internazionale in 2023]]
On 22 June 2021, Çalhanoğlu signed a three-year contract with Serie A club [[Inter Milan]], the city-rival of his previous club, on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news |last=Barker |first=Gabby |date=22 June 2021 |title=Calhanoglu, Atlético's 'alternative', leaves Milan for Inter |url=https://sportsfinding.com/calhanoglu-atleticos-alternative-leaves-milan-for-inter/102229/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221114173304/https://sportsfinding.com/calhanoglu-atleticos-alternative-leaves-milan-for-inter/102229/ |archive-date=14 November 2022 |access-date=22 June 2021 |work=Sports Finding |language=en-GB |url-status=dead}}</ref>

Çalhanoğlu scored and assisted a goal on his Inter Milan debut, a 4–0 win over [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]] on the opening day of the [[2021–22 Serie A]] season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Stroud |first=James |date=21 August 2021 |title=Hakan Calhanoglu scores rocket and bags an assist 15 minutes into Inter debut vs Genoa |url=https://www.givemesport.com/1741108-hakan-calhanoglu-scores-rocket-and-bags-an-assist-15-minutes-into-inter-debut-vs-genoa/ |access-date=25 August 2021 |website=GiveMeSport}}</ref> He went on to score seven goals and notch twelve assists in the league, and scored in the [[2022 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia final]] victory against [[Juventus FC|Juventus]], but it was his former team Milan that went on to lift the league title. On 4 October 2022, he scored his first Champions League goal with Inter in a 1–0 win over [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite news |date=4 October 2022 |title=Inter Milan 1–0 Barcelona: Xavi furious at 'injustice' in Champions League defeat |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63080315 |access-date=5 October 2022 |work=[[BBC Sport]] |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 14 March 2023, he was named Player of the Match in the Champions League round of 16 second leg away match against [[FC Porto|Porto]], which ended in a goalless draw and qualification to the quarter-final for the first time in twelve years for Inter Milan, by winning 1–0 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/027f-1788cb13be30-6eeeb762c03a-1000--highlights-report-resolute-inter-through-after-draw/ |title=Porto 0–0 Inter (agg: 0–1): Nerazzurri hold firm to reach Champions League last eight |work=UEFA |date=14 March 2023 |access-date=15 March 2023}}</ref>

[[File:Edison ndreca inter egnatia.jpg|thumb|upright|175px|Çalhanoğlu (left) playing with Internazionale in a friendly in August 2023]]
On 5 June 2023, he agreed to extend his contract with [[Inter Milan]] for another 4 years, lasting until 2027.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inter and Hakan Çalhanoğlu together until 2027 |url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/hakan-calhanoglu-inter-contract-extension-2027 |access-date=8 July 2023 |website=Inter.it}}</ref> On 4 November 2023, he scored his tenth consecutive penalty in a 2–1 away victory over [[Atalanta BC|Atalanta]], only fewer than [[Romelu Lukaku]] with 14; in addition, he managed to equal [[Sükrü Gülesin]]'s record as the highest Turkish scorer in Serie A with 36 goals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inter extends lead with win over Atalanta |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-nz/football/serie-a/articles-video/inter-extends-ead-with-win-over-atalanta-2023-11-04 |access-date=5 November 2023 |website=beIN SPORTS |language=en-nz |date=4 November 2023}}</ref> He finished the [[2023–24 Serie A|2023–24 season]] with a personal best, scoring 13 goals in Serie A.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hakan Calhanoglu is the best midfielder of the 2023/24 Serie A season |url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/hakan-calhanoglu-best-midfielder-serie-a-23-24 |access-date=22 June 2024 |website=Inter.it |date=24 May 2024}}</ref>

In the 2024–25 season, he scored four goals during the [[2024–25 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] campaign, including a penalty against Barcelona in the semifinal, helping his club advance to the [[2025 UEFA Champions League final|final]] and becoming the first Turkish player to achieve this feat twice.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ulucam |first=Yusuf |url=https://www.turkiyetoday.com/sports/hakan-calhanoglu-aims-for-history-as-inter-milan-face-psg-in-champions-league-final-3202167 |title=Hakan Calhanoglu to make history as Inter Milan faces PSG in Champions League final |publisher=Türkiye Today |date=30 May 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
{{Quote box|width=25%|align=right|quoted=1|quote=It's thanks to the Germans that I became a footballer. But playing for the Turkish national team is an honour. I want to be Turkey's [[Mesut Özil]].|source=— Çalhanoğlu explaining his decision to represent Turkey to ''[[Milliyet]]''.<ref name=FIFA/>}}
Born in [[Germany]], Çalhanoğlu opted to play for Turkey, qualifying for them through his family's origins in [[Trabzon]].<ref name=fifa/> He played for the country at youth international level, including the [[2013 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] on home soil.<ref name=fifa/> Turkey reached the last 16 before elimination by [[France national under-20 football team|France]]. In their second group game on 28 June, Çalhanoğlu scored Turkey's equaliser in a 2–1 win over [[Australia national under-20 soccer team|Australia]] at the [[Hüseyin Avni Aker Stadium]] in his ancestral city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Australia – Turkey|url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=259235/match=300232850/report.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703002140/http://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=259235/match=300232850/report.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 July 2013|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=FIFA|date=28 June 2013}}</ref>

[[File:AUT vs. TUR 2016-03-29 (346).jpg|thumb|Çalhanoğlu playing for Turkey in 2016]]

He made his senior international debut on 6 September 2013 in a World Cup qualifier in [[Kayseri]], replacing [[Gökhan Töre]] for the last eight minutes of a 5–0 win against [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]] in [[Fatih Terim]]'s first match back in charge.<ref>{{cite news|title=Terim enjoys Turkey return against Andorra|url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/season=2014/matches/round=2000294/match=2008629/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113072018/http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/season=2014/matches/round=2000294/match=2008629/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 November 2012|access-date=6 March 2015|publisher=UEFA|date=6 September 2013}}</ref> He made his first start on 25 May 2014 in a 2–1 friendly win against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] at Dublin's [[Aviva Stadium]], making way for [[Olcan Adın]] after 61 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/rep-ire-vs-turkey/report/308393|title=Match Report – Republic of Ireland 1–2 Turkey|publisher=Sky Sports|date=26 May 2014|access-date=6 March 2015}}</ref>

Çalhanoğlu was sharing a hotel room with national team defender [[Ömer Toprak]] in October 2013 after a World Cup qualifying defeat to the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], when Gökhan Töre and an unknown armed friend entered the room, and threatened both roommates at gunpoint, ostensibly due to Töre's ex-girlfriend dating a friend of Toprak.<ref name=":0">{{cite web |last=Sarigul |first=Emre |date=16 November 2014 |title=How a love story and a firearm incident tore the Turkey team apart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/nov/16/turkey-gokhan-tore-omer-toprak-hakan-calhanoglu |access-date=29 August 2015 |website=[[The Guardian]] |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The incident was hidden from Turkish media, but Çalhanoğlu revealed it to Germany's [[ZDF]] television channel.<ref name=":0" /> Töre did not return to the national team until October 2014, when both Çalhanoğlu and Toprak were injured. The following month, with both players back to fitness and form, both were left out by Terim for a friendly against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and a [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] match against [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]] while Töre remained. Çalhanoğlu questioned his omission from the team, while Terim defended his own decision and said that Töre deserved to be forgiven.<ref name=":0" /> In June 2015, Çalhanoğlu and Töre reconciled.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weber|first1=Jens|title=Reports: Turkey's Gokhan Tore and Hakan Calhanoglu settle row|url=http://www.espnfc.com/german-bundesliga/story/2503468/turkey-says-gokhan-tore-and-hakan-calhanoglu-settled-row|access-date=29 August 2015|publisher=ESPN FC|date=24 June 2015}}</ref>

On 31 March 2015, Çalhanoğlu scored his first international goal in a 2–1 friendly win away to [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]], a 30-yard strike with three minutes remaining.<ref>{{cite web|title=International Friendly: Luxembourg 1 Turkey 2|url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/luxembourg-1-turkey-2-calhanoglu-stakes-claim-late-winner|access-date=31 March 2015|publisher=Four Four Two|date=31 March 2015}}</ref> He scored two more in a 4–0 home friendly win over [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] on 8 June, the latter being a free kick.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/football/match/_/gameId/420806/bulgaria-turquia |title=Turkey 4–0 Bulgaria |publisher=ESPN |date=8 June 2015 }}</ref> His first competitive goal came on 10 October, a cross which secured a 2–0 away win over the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] event.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Raiman |first1=Vojtěch |date=10 October 2015 |title=Turkey crash Czech party to reclaim third place |url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/0253-0d80a09d8232-719c4c7a359f-1000--turkey-crash-czech-party-to-reclaim-third-place/ |access-date=11 October 2015 |publisher=UEFA}}</ref>

Çalhanoğlu became the first Turk to score against [[England national football team|England]], in the 11th match between the two nations, a friendly at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]] on 22 May 2016, in which he equalized in the 2–1 defeat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rudd|first1=Lewis|title=Hakan Calhanoglu makes history by becoming the first Turkey player to score v England|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/05/22/hakan-calhanoglu-makes-history-by-becoming-the-first-turkey-player-to-score-v-england-5898729/|access-date=22 May 2016|work=Metro|date=22 May 2016}}</ref> Later that month, on 31 May, he was selected in the 23-man squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2016]].<ref>{{cite web |title=A Milli Takım'ın EURO 2016 nihai kadrosu açıklandı |url=http://www.tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=202&ftxtID=25232 |access-date=31 May 2016 |publisher=Turkish Football Association}}</ref>

On 22 March 2019, Çalhanoğlu scored the second goal of Turkey's 2–0 victory over [[Albania national football team|Albania]] in their opening [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying|UEFA Euro 2020 qualifier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/albania-vs-turkey/403210|title=Albania 0–2 Turkey|publisher=Sky Sports|date=22 March 2019|access-date=29 October 2019}}</ref> On 1 June 2021, he was named in the Turkish squad for the postponed [[UEFA Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=202&ftxtID=35271 |title=A Millî Takımın nihai kadrosu açıklandı |trans-title=Final squad of the national team announced |work=Turkish Football Federation |date=1 June 2021 |access-date=1 June 2021 |language=tr}}</ref> In March 2022, he became his nation's captain, following the retirement of [[Burak Yılmaz]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/inter-midfielder-hakan-calhanoglu-to-captain-turkey-in-friendly-against-italiy-italian-media-report-34815762 |title=Inter Midfielder Hakan Calhanoglu To Captain Turkey In Friendly Against Italiy, Italian Media Report |publisher=OneFootball |date=29 March 2022 }}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, he was called up to the 26-man squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]],<ref>{{cite news |date=7 June 2024 |title=A Millî Takımımızın EURO 2024 Aday Kadrosu Açıklandı |trans-title=EURO 2024 Candidate Squad of Our National Team Announced |url=https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=202&ftxtID=44561 |language=tr |publisher=[[Turkish Football Federation]] |access-date=7 June 2024}}</ref> becoming the second Turkish player to feature in three European tournaments, following [[Rüştü Reçber]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b29ce033a7b-f0319eea90ab-1000--turkiye-3-1-georgia-arda-guler-thunderbolt-lights-up-thr/ |title=Türkiye 3–1 Georgia: Arda Güler thunderbolt lights up thrilling win |publisher=UEFA |date=18 June 2024 }}</ref> On 11 October 2025, he made his 100th international appearance in a 6–1 away win over [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] during the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/inter-milan-star-proud-landmark-133000525.html |title=Inter Milan Star ‘Proud’ Of Landmark 100th Appearance For Turkey: ‘It’s Not Easy’ |publisher=Yahoo Sports |date=12 October 2025 }}</ref>

==Style of play==
Çalhanoğlu has been likened to [[Mesut Özil]], another German-born [[midfielder]] of Turkish ancestry.<ref name=talksport>{{cite web|last1=Mannion|first1=Damian|title=Arsenal transfer news: the starlet being compared to Ozil|url=http://talksport.com/football/arsenal-transfer-news-starlet-being-compared-ozil-13121171482|access-date=15 April 2015|publisher=[[Talksport]]|date=11 December 2013|archive-date=3 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234926/http://talksport.com/football/arsenal-transfer-news-starlet-being-compared-ozil-13121171482|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vélez García|first1=Raquel|title=Chelsea Suffer Blow in 'New Mesut Ozil' Pursuit – Report|url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/chelsea-suffer-blow-new-mesut-ozil-pursuit-report-1448515|access-date=15 April 2015|work=[[International Business Times]]|date=14 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Doyle|first1=Mark|title='Calhanoglu is the new Ozil' – Schafer|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/15/germany/2013/12/29/4509068/calhanoglu-is-the-new-ozil-schafer|access-date=15 April 2015|publisher=Goal.com|date=29 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jefferson|first1=Ben|title=Arsenal and Liverpool in battle for 'new Mesut Ozil' Hakan Calhanoglu|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/447662/Arsenal-and-Liverpool-in-battle-for-new-Mesut-Ozil-Hakan-Calhanoglu|access-date=15 April 2015|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=9 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Man Utd-linked Calhanoglu's future addressed by AC Milan boss Pioli {{!}} Goal.com|url=https://www.goal.com/en/news/man-utd-linked-calhanoglus-future-addressed-by-ac-milan-boss/u3ckt7mijy961j0h0m9gyhtba|access-date=2020-12-24|website=www.goal.com|language=en}}</ref> He expressed a desire to be the equivalent of Özil in the Turkey national team.<ref name=FIFA>{{cite news|title=Leverkusen – Calhanoglu à la conquête de l'Europe|trans-title=Leverkusen – Çalhanoğlu ready to conquer Europe|url=http://fr.fifa.com/world-match-centre/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid/244/012/0/|access-date=11 October 2015|publisher=FIFA|date=15 September 2014|language=fr|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150917154450/http://fr.fifa.com/world-match-centre/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid/244/012/0/|archive-date=17 September 2015}}</ref>

A set-piece specialist, he is known for scoring from [[Free kick (association football)|free kicks]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Tweedale|first1=Alistair|title=Cristiano Ronaldo free-kick goals are rare, show WhoScored.com stats|url=https://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/9804389/cristiano-ronaldo-free-kick-goals-are-rare-show-whoscoredcom-stats|access-date=16 April 2015|publisher=Sky Sports|date=14 April 2015}}</ref> and models his set-piece technique on the ''[[Knuckleball#Association football|knuckleball]]'' free kicks of [[Cristiano Ronaldo]] and especially [[Juninho Pernambucano]].<ref name="talksport" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2057661-20-best-goals-of-the-201314-bundesliga-season |title=20 Best Goals of the 2013/14 Bundesliga season |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Whitney |first1=Clark |date=12 May 2014 |access-date=28 June 2020 }}</ref> In addition to his ability to score with power and accuracy from direct free kicks with his right foot,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/scholl-basler-calhanoglu-arango-hassler-best-ever-free-kick-takers-478529.jsp |title=Scholl, Basler, Calhanoglu and the Bundesliga's best ever free-kick takers |publisher=Bundesliga |access-date=28 June 2020 |archive-date=9 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200809113718/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/scholl-basler-calhanoglu-arango-hassler-best-ever-free-kick-takers-478529.jsp |url-status=dead }}</ref> he is also known for his ability to [[Curl (association football)|bend]] the ball, and his set-piece delivery.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tighe |first1=Sam |date=16 July 2015 |title=Hakan Calhanoglu Will Be the Emerging Face of the Bundesliga This Season |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2523372-hakan-calhanoglu-will-be-the-emerging-face-of-the-bundesliga-this-season |access-date=28 June 2020 |publisher=Bleacher Report}}</ref> In December 2013, [[Talksport]] called him "a [[playmaker]] destined for the top", praising his dedication and passing ability.<ref name="talksport" /> Former [[England national football team|England]] international [[Owen Hargreaves]] said on [[BT Sport]] in August 2015 that Çalhanoğlu's style of play would fit [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] or Tottenham Hotspur.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tr.eurosport.com/futbol/super-lig/2015-2016/hakan-calhanoglu-icin-onemli-aciklama-liverpool-ve-tottenham._sto4879950/story.shtml|title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu için önemli açıklama! "Liverpool ve Tottenham..."|trans-title=Important information for Hakan Çalhanoğlu ! "Liverpool and Tottenham..."|publisher=Eurosport|language=tr|date=27 August 2015|access-date=28 August 2015}}</ref>

Despite mostly positive reception in his late teens and early twenties, in recent years, however, he has drawn some criticism as well; his pace was deemed insufficient for a winger, a position he adopted due to absence of his natural classic "number 10" attacking midfield role in the preferred formations of his teams, particularly [[AC Milan]]. He has also been criticized in the media for his lack of physical attributes and overall inconsistency of his performances. However, his [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]], technique, passing (both short and long), [[Cross (association football)|crossing]], and vision, as well as his eye for goal and striking ability from distance, have been referred to as his strengths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/club/ac-milan/103/blog/post/3480809/hakan-calhanoglu-growing-into-a-no10-ac-milan-should-build-around|title=Hakan Calhanoglu growing into a No.10 AC Milan should build around|publisher=ESPN FC|author=Sumeet Paul|date=2 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=2 July 2017 |title=Calciomercato Milan, chi è Calhanoglu: il mago delle punizioni che ha scelto la Turchia |url=https://www.goal.com/it/notizie/calciomercato-milan-chi-e-calhanoglu-il-mago-delle-punizioni-che-/1egpfhi5nik661nhqvyqqph7uj |access-date=28 June 2020 |website=[[Goal.com]] |language=it}}</ref> Çalhanoğlu has also been used in deeper midfield positions throughout his career, including in a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|holding role]], in which he usually operates as a [[Midfielder#Deep-lying playmaker (Strolling 10)|deep-lying playmaker]], as an offensive–minded [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]], known as the ''[[Midfielder#Mezzala|mezzala]]'' role in Italian football jargon, or even in more [[Forward (association football)|offensive roles]] on occasion, as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|second striker]], for example.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chioffi |first=Stefano |date=24 May 2014 |title=Calhanoglu, nove gol al debutto in Bundesliga |url=https://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/talent-scout/2014/05/24-513032/calhanoglu_nove_gol_al_debutto_in_bundesliga |access-date=29 October 2019 |website=[[Il Corriere dello Sport]] |language=it}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=16 May 2019 |title=Inter con Candreva dal 1'. Juve, premio per Barzagli. Napoli: c'è Mertens |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/calcio/fantanews/16-05-2019/inter-tocca-lautaro-milan-confermato-juve-torna-bernardeschi-3301655080890.shtml |access-date=24 June 2020 |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=it}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Çalhanoğlu was born in Mannheim, Germany, to Turkish parents originally from [[Bayburt]], Turkey.<ref name="2013 TFF Interview">{{cite news |author=Selim Şakarcan |date=1 May 2013 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu: "Orta sahanın genç virtüözü" |url=https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=286&ftxtID=17899 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201024143211/https://www.tff.org/default.aspx?pageID=286&ftxtID=17899 |archive-date=24 October 2020 |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[Turkish Football Federation]] |language=tr}}</ref> Çalhanoğlu married his childhood sweetheart Sinem Gündoğdu, in Mannheim, in 2017.<ref name="Marriage">{{cite news |date=23 April 2017 |title=Milli futbolcu Hakan Çalhanoğlu evlendi |url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/yasam/milli-futbolcu-hakan-calhanoglu-evlendi,EyiAodJhaEyhRs2rHe_THg |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201024155957/https://www.ntv.com.tr/yasam/milli-futbolcu-hakan-calhanoglu-evlendi,xgYT11WBXUq5QZPJbyjV7A |archive-date=24 October 2020 |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[NTV (Turkey)]] |language=tr}}</ref> The couple had alleged marital problems,<ref name="2018 Marriage News (1)">{{cite news |date=2 August 2018 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu ayrılığı duyurdu (Eşi Sinem Çalhanoğlu'dan iddialara yanıt) |url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/yasam/hakan-calhanoglu-ayriligi-duyurdu-esi-sinem-calhanogludan-iddialara-yanit,QDQ1_YE8X0-PdQsmSrQwfA |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201024161551/https://www.ntv.com.tr/galeri/yasam/hakan-calhanoglu-ayriligi-duyurdu-esi-sinem-calhanogludan-iddialara-yanit,QDQ1_YE8X0-PdQsmSrQwfA |archive-date=24 October 2020 |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[NTV (Turkey)]] |language=tr}}</ref> because of which Çalhanoğlu decided to file for divorce, but in 2018,<ref name="2018 Marriage News (2)">{{cite news |date=2 August 2018 |title=Sinem Gündoğdu ve Hakan Çalhanoğlu boşanıyor! Hakan Çalhanoğlu aldatıldı mı? |url=https://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2018/08/02/sinem-gundogdu-ve-hakan-calhanoglu-bosaniyor-hakan-calhanoglu-aldatildi-mi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201024162033/https://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2018/08/02/sinem-gundogdu-ve-hakan-calhanoglu-bosaniyor-hakan-calhanoglu-aldatildi-mi |archive-date=24 October 2020 |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] |language=tr}}</ref> the couple reportedly made up.<ref name="2019 Marriage News (2)">{{cite news |date=22 May 2019 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu eşi Sinem Çalhanoğlu ile 2. evlilik yıldönümünü kutladı |url=https://www.haberturk.com/hakan-calhanoglu-esi-sinem-calhanoglu-ile-2-evlilik-yildonumunu-kutladi-magazin-haberleri-2471602-magazin |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[Haberturk]] |language=tr}}</ref><ref name="2019 Marriage News (3)">{{cite news |date=21 November 2018 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu ile Sinem Çalhanoğlu barıştı |url=https://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2018/11/21/hakan-calhanoglu-ile-sinem-calhanoglu-baristi |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201024161042/https://www.sabah.com.tr/magazin/2018/11/21/hakan-calhanoglu-ile-sinem-calhanoglu-baristi |archive-date=24 October 2020 |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[Sabah (newspaper)|Sabah]] |language=tr}}</ref> The couple welcomed their daughter, Liya, born in Mannheim, in March 2019.<ref name="First Kid (1)">{{cite news |date=6 March 2019 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu baba oldu |url=https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/sporarena/hakan-calhanoglu-baba-oldu-41140460 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20201024162638/https://www.hurriyet.com.tr/sporarena/burak-yilmaz-acikladi-benim-yasimdaki-dunya-yildizlari-41644899 |archive-date=24 October 2020 |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[Hürriyet]] |language=tr}}</ref><ref name="First Kid (2)">{{cite news |date=6 March 2019 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu baba oldu |url=https://www.ntv.com.tr/spor/hakan-calhanoglu-baba-oldu,Af-PpUUQI0iL08IUkEg0qQ |access-date=24 October 2020 |publisher=[[NTV (Turkey)]] |language=tr |agency=[[Demirören News Agency]]}}</ref> They also have two boys, Ayaz and Asil Can (born November 2023).<ref>{{cite news |date=21 November 2023 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu üçüncü kez baba oldu |url=https://www.haberturk.com/hakan-calhanoglu-ucuncu-kez-baba-oldu-magazin-haberleri-3638760-magazin |access-date=4 December 2023 |newspaper=Habertürk |language=tr}}</ref>

[[Muhammed Çalhanoğlu|Muhammed]], younger brother of Hakan, is also a professional footballer.<ref>{{cite web |date=8 August 2017 |title=Çalhanoğlu Karagümrük'te |url=http://www.amatorlig.net/calhanoglu-karagumrukte.html |access-date=9 August 2017 |website=Amatör Lig Net |language=tr}}</ref> The younger Çalhanoğlu was also formed at [[SV Waldhof Mannheim|Waldhof Mannheim]] and [[Karlsruher SC]], and went on to play in the lower divisions of Austrian and Turkish football.<ref>{{cite news |date=27 July 2016 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu'nun kardeşi Muhammed Çalhanoğlu, Gümüşhanespor'da |url=https://www.haberturk.com/spor/futbol/haber/1272775-hakan-calhanoglunun-kardesi-muhammed-calhanoglu-gumushanesporda |access-date=10 October 2017 |publisher=[[Habertürk|Haber Turk]] |language=tr}}</ref> Similarly, his cousin [[Kerim Çalhanoğlu]] is also a footballer, and also played for [[SV Waldhof Mannheim|Waldhof Mannheim]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Brunetti |first=Nico |url=https://www.fussball.de/newsdetail/die-calhanoglus-vier-kicker-ein-trainer/-/article-id/159376 |title=Die Calhanoglus: Vier Kicker, ein Trainer |trans-title=The Çalhanoğlus: Four footballers, one coach |website=Fussball.de |date=14 December 2016 |access-date=5 March 2021 |language=de}}</ref>

In January 2017, Çalhanoğlu posted a video to [[Twitter]] [[2017 Turkish constitutional referendum 'Yes' campaign|supporting]] Turkish president [[Recep Tayyip Erdoğan]] ahead of the [[2017 Turkish constitutional referendum]]. Bayer Leverkusen spokesman [[Dirk Muschiol|Dirk Mesch]] confirmed the club discussed the tweet with Çalhanoğlu.<ref>{{cite news |date=30 January 2017 |title=Leverkusens Calhanoglu unterstützt türkischen Präsidenten |url=https://www.focus.de/sport/fussball/bundesliga1/recep-tayyip-erdogan-leverkusens-calhanoglu-unterstuetzt-tuerkischen-praesidenten_id_6563193.html |access-date=5 January 2018 |publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] |language=de}}</ref>

On 11 October 2019, following [[Cenk Tosun]]'s goal in a 1–0 home win over [[Albania national football team|Albania]] in a [[Euro 2020 qualifiers|Euro 2020 qualifier]], Çalhanoğlu was one of the Turkish players who participated in a "[[Salute#Military salutes|military salute]]" [[goal celebration]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50019304 |title=Turkey v Albania (1–0) |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 October 2019 |access-date=29 October 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/uefa-to-examine-turkey-military-celebrations-calhanoglu-and-demi-82485 |title=UEFA to examine Turkey 'military' celebrations: Calhanoglu and Demiral at risk |publisher=CalcioMercato.com |date=12 October 2019 |access-date=29 October 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50041529 |title=Euro 2020: Uefa probes Turkey footballers' military salute |publisher=BBC Sport |date=14 October 2019 |access-date=29 October 2019 }}</ref> That same day, he stated his open support for the [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria]] with a post on [[Twitter]], which drew criticism from numerous Italian football fans on social media.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://it.eurosport.com/calcio/serie-a/2019-2020/demiral-e-under-nella-bufera-per-i-tweet-a-sostegno-dell-offensiva-in-siria_sto7494708/story.shtml |title=Demiral, Calhanoglu e Under nella bufera per i tweet a sostegno dell'offensiva turca contro i curdi |publisher=Eurosport |language=it |last1=Dolci |first1=Stefano |date=23 June 2022 |access-date=23 June 2022}}</ref>

He is a supporter of [[Galatasaray S.K. (football team)|Galatasaray]] and in an interview he expressed his desire to play there in the future for a part of his career as he spent his childhood dreaming of winning trophies with Galatasaray.<ref>{{cite web |date=11 October 2019 |title=Hakan Çalhanoğlu'ndan Galatasaray açıklaması: Taraftarlar ümitlenebilirler |url=https://www.ntvspor.net/futbol/hakan-calhanoglu-ndan-galatasaray-aciklamasi-taraftarlar-umitlenebilirler-62b367381193c50aa40e9e56 |access-date=29 October 2019 |publisher=Ntvspor |language=tr}}</ref>

== Charity ==
In 2025, Çalhanoğlu partnered with the Web3 game ''My Lovely Planet'' to launch the “Çalhanoğlu Forest” reforestation project in Kuşadası, Turkey. The initiative began with the planting of 10,000 native trees on land damaged by wildfires in 2024.

